  - Role-based access: Admin, Agent, Ops, Finance with per-page and per-action guards

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks: React (with TypeScript), adopt a component-based architecture; use a state management approach (e.g., Redux Toolkit or React Context) for cross-component data sharing.
- Data safety:
  - All API results use data ?? [] patterns; arrays guarded with Array.isArray checks.
  - useState defaults: useState<BookingDraft[]>([]) for arrays; useState<BookingDraft> for object data with defaults; ensure proper initialization.
- UI Components:
  - Reusable Card components with soft shadows, borders, and hover states per design system.
  - Form controls with accessible labels, focus states, and validation messages.
  - Stepper / progress bar with accessible aria roles and keyboard navigation.
  - Image cards with resort imagery and highlights for fast filtering.
  - Inline validation and contextual help.
- Data handling:
  - Validate all inputs; enforce required fields at each step.
  - Ensure that all arrays (itinerary items, attachments, supplier references) are initialized to [] and guarded before mapping/filtering.
- API integration readiness:
  - Endpoints should be typed; handle 4xx/5xx gracefully; provide user-friendly error messages.
- Performance:
  - Lazy-load resort results; debounce search inputs; optimize rendering of lengthy itineraries.
- Accessibility:
  - ARIA labels for complex widgets; keyboard accessible controls; color contrast compliance.

### Backend
- APIs:
  - Booking API: createBooking, updateBooking, getBooking, searchClient, getResorts, searchRates, createItineraryItem, addAttachment, setPaymentSchedule, generateProposal, etc.
  - Client API: searchClients, createClient, updateClient, fetchClientDetails (passport, contact prefs, billing).
  - Resort Bible API: searchResorts, getResortDetails, listRooms
  - Rates API: listRatePlans, calculateCommission
  - Attachments API: uploadAttachment, listAttachments
  - Payments API: schedulePayment, updatePayment, paymentStatus
  - Approvals API: requestApproval, approveBooking
  - Template API: renderTemplate (DOCX/PDF) with data payload
- Database Tables (high-level):
  - clients (id, name, contact, passport, vipFlags, preferences, billingDetails, history)
  - bookings (id, clientId, resortId, roomCategoryId, ratePlanId, commissionModel, status, lifecycleStage, quotes, createdAt, updatedAt, createdBy)
  - booking_items (id, bookingId, dayIndex, activity, transferDetails, startTime, endTime)
  - payment_schedules (id, bookingId, milestoneName, dueDate, amount, currency, status)
  - attachments (id, bookingId, fileName, url, type, uploadedAt)
  - supplier_references (id, bookingId, supplierName, referenceCode, notes)
  - approvals (id, bookingId, stage, status, approverId, dueDate, notes)
  - itineraries (id, bookingId, dayIndex, activities)
  - resort_bibles (id, location, transferTime, kidsPolicy, roomTypes, seasonality, partners, perks, media)
  - templates (id, type, templateFile, placeholders)
- Data validation:
  - Strict server-side validation mirroring frontend rules; ensure null-safe data handling.
- Security:
  - JWT/OAuth-based authentication; RBAC checks on endpoints; audit logs for critical actions.
- Logging & Monitoring:
  - Instrumentation for booking lifecycle events, conflicts detected, and template generation.

### Integration
- Connected data flows:
  - Booking Create/Edit Wizard feeds into Booking Lifecycle: timeline, attachments, supplier references, and internal handoffs.
  - Itinerary and transfers become part of the booking’s core itinerary, which is persisted and exposed in Booking Detail.
  - Proposal & Handover templates are generated on demand from the booking data and offered for download/export.
- Data consistency:
  - Ensure data normalization between step components and detail view; use centralized booking data store to prevent drift.
- Error handling:
  - Central error boundary; user-friendly error messages; retry strategies for transient failures.

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on Booking Create / Edit Wizard.
2. Step 1 – Client: Search existing clients; select or create a new client; on selection, auto-fill client fields; continue.
3. Step 2 – Resort & Room: Use Resort Bible search to filter and choose resort; select room category; view transfer times and inclusions; proceed.
4. Step 3 – Rates & Commission: Pick a rate plan; choose a commission model; see auto-calculated commission; proceed.
5. Step 4 – Payment Schedule & Deadlines: Define a milestone-driven payment schedule; set due dates and amounts; define deadlines; proceed.
6. Step 5 – Itinerary & Transfers: Build day-by-day itinerary; add activities/transfers; ensure no timing conflicts; proceed.
7. Step 6 – Attachments & Supplier References: Upload supplier documents; capture references; proceed.
8. Step 7 – Review & Save: Review all data; fix any validation issues; choose Save Draft or Save as Quote or Confirm Booking; if chosen, trigger conflict/deadline checks and final validations.
9. Automated checks run in real-time or on demand (conflicts, deadlines).
10. After a successful save, navigate to Booking Detail with full lifecycle timeline and details; optionally generate Proposal/Handover document.
11. From Booking Detail, access to edit, manage, or generate templates as needed.

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models: 
  - BookingDraft vs Booking
  - Client, Resort, RoomCategory
  - RatePlan, CommissionModel
  - PaymentSchedule, ItineraryItem
  - Attachments, SupplierReferences
  - TimelineEvent, Approvals
- API Endpoints:
  - POST /api/bookings (createBooking)
  - PUT /api/bookings/{id} (updateBooking)
  - GET /api/bookings/{id} (getBooking)
  - GET /api/clients?query=... (searchClients)
  - POST /api/clients (createClient)
  - GET /api/resorts (searchResorts)
  - GET /api/resorts/{id} (getResortDetails)
  - GET /api/rates (listRatePlans)
  - POST /api/payments/schedule (schedulePayment)
  - POST /api/templates/render (renderTemplate)
  - POST /api/templates/generateCannedProposal (optional)
  - POST /api/attachments (uploadAttachment)
  - POST /api/approvals (requestApproval)
- Security:
  - OAuth2 / JWT with roles: Admin, Agent, Ops, Finance
  - Permissions gated on pages and actions (view, edit, create, delete, approve)
- Validation:
  - All inputs validated client-side and server-side
  - Use data ?? [] for arrays, Array.isArray() guards, and optional chaining
  - Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {} 

- Validation Rules:
  - Client: required; if new client, validate mandatory fields (name, contact, billing)
  - Resort/Room: required; ensure room category availability
  - Rate Plan: required; compatible with dates and policy
  - Payment Schedule: milestones must align with booking dates; sums must equal total price
  - Itinerary: at least one day; no overlapping times; transfers valid
  - Attachments: optional but must be valid types; supplier references may be required for certain bookings
  - Approvals: required if booking exceeds threshold or requires Ops/Finance signoff
- Data Flow:
  - Booking state persisted in backend; live synchronization for timeline and status
  - Templates generate using booking payload; placeholders replaced with actual data

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The wizard supports create and edit flows with all seven steps, including client creation and auto-population.
- [ ] All arrays are initialized with [] and guarded with Array.isArray() before map/filter/reduce usage.
- [ ] Null/undefined values are never passed to array methods; results from API are normalized using data ?? [] or Array.isArray checks.
- [ ] Validation runs at each step; Save Draft is always possible; Save as Quote and Confirm Booking are disabled until validation passes.
- [ ] Conflict and deadline checks run in real-time (or on save) and surface actionable error messages.
- [ ] Booking Detail shows full lifecycle timeline and all fields (itinerary, resort, room, rate, commission, payments, deadlines, references, attachments, internal notes, approvals).
- [ ] Proposal & Handover templates generate correctly from booking data and produce valid DOCX/PDF outputs with proper placeholders replaced.
- [ ] Role-based access controls prevent unauthorized actions; Admin/Agent/Ops/Finance permissions enforced.
- [ ] Accessible keyboard navigation, responsive UI, and performance considerations (debounced search, lazy rendering, etc.)

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project’s design system:

- Color Palette:
  - Primary: White (#FFFFFF)
  - Accent: Olive Green (#8A9A5B)
  - Neutrals: #F6F6F6, #EEEEEE
  - Text: #222222; secondary #888888
  - Gold: #C6AB62
  - Imagery: Luxury, warm-toned photography
- Typography & Layout:
  - Headings: Elegant serif (Playfair Display, Georgia)
  - Body: Sans-serif (Lato, Helvetica Neue)
  - Alignment: Left content; center headers for callouts
  - Spacing: Generous; clear blocks
- Key Design Elements:
  - Cards: White with subtle shadows; 4-8px radius; dividers; hover lift
  - Navigation: Sticky header; active states with accent underline
  - Data Visualization: Minimalist; no heavy charts
  - Interactive elements: Olive green buttons; focus states; subtle shadows
- Design Philosophy:
  - Luxury, modern, minimal; clarity, calm professionalism; premium yet usable
  - Generous whitespace; visually balanced; minimal noise
  - Premium experience with trustworthy, efficient operations

